Introduction

The emissions dataset consists of a number variables hand picked by me and wrangled and merged from 11 different datasets all downloaded from the Gapminder or Databank websites. I chose this dataset for my project because I am working on something similar for the Data Visualization with D3 Module on the same Nanodegree, the visualization can be viewed at http://sijvizproject.esy.es/ (note that the visualization is not ready yet and is still being developed)

With everything in the news about global warming, I hoped to investigate for myself based on publicly available data. Since I at the start of this project knew little to nothing about global warming, my goal for this project is to educate myself on it.

From the very start, Emissions yearly and Emissions capita I felt should be the variables of interest and all subsequent analysis will be baed around them, I will include a univariate section using histograms, a bivariate using a number of plot types and finally a multivariate section typically using Continent the only categorical variable I added to the dataset. The plan is to then build a predictive model if possible and see if I can predict either the emissions yearly or capita given a number of features.

Univariate Analysis

Histograms Emissions Yearly Histogram

This seems to be very right skewed with lots of outliers however, A log transformation makes it more normally distributed. Adding the continent variable shows a clear pattern in how different continents contribute to global emission. African countries generally contribute the least with not a lot of variation, Asian countries show a lot of variation from not contributing a lot to contributing a very high amount, this is to be expected taking into account countries like China but just as in the case with Africa, many of the countries are under-developed and would contribute little to emission. Europe shows most of its countries contributing a fair bit with a handful of contries contributing a lot for example, the UK, Germany and France. The histogram also appears to be bi-modal, many yearly emissions counts seem to fall within those ranges.

This is a rightly skewed distribution for the percentage with access to electricity, an interesting to note is that both the 3rd quartile and Max are 100, this tells us that the 3rd quartile(upper 25%) have a population with a 100% access to electricity and that over 50% have populations with over 90.9% access to electricity. This feature can also benefit from a little bi and multi-variate analysis.

A good place to start is with a scatterplot matrix to show all the variables relationship to each other. Dataset is subset only for the year 2000 and some columns are excluded

Right out of the box without any transformations, some variables look to be highly correlated. Populations and Emissions yearly Total with a correlation of 0.614, Literacy rate and access to electricity with 0.8, GDP and emissions yearly total, emission per capita with energy use. There are other relatively strong correlations though not as strong as the ones mentioned.

Structure of the dataset

There are 7,044 observations in the dataset with 13 features(Country, Year, Populations, Emissions_Yearly_Total, Emissions_Capita, Global Population, Continent, Literacy % rate, percentage with access to electricty, % of land area with Forest, GDP, Energy Use, % of energy use that is Alternative energy).

Main features of the dataset Emissions yearly and Emissions per capita

Both features are relatively similar, the are also different and say very different things, a country with a high yearly emission for example may have a low, high or any emissions per capita and vice versa.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest? Id say all of them, I put together the dataset and handpicked all the features in it with the hope that they will help, whether or not they do remains to be seen.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset? Not exactly, I did have to include the continents variable so I could have a categorical variable to split the data on but that was done by merging with a contry-continent dataset.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this? Yes. A number of logarithmic transformations had to be applied to both the emissions features as well as populations.

Doing the same for emissions Yearly

As expected both histograms show a similar pattern to that seen for the overall, taking into account of course that a handful of countries are emitting more in subsequent years. A bar chart showing the emissions for each continent might help.

In an earlier histogram, we saw how different continents contribute to the global emissions. Continents like Asia for example show a very wide spread, implying there are countries within the continent across the entire spectrum low to high emissions. It would be helpful to know exactly which countries within which continents are driving up the total emissions for a particular continent and which ones are contributing less. A heat map can help visualize this and it can also show how it has changed across the years.

Final Plots and Summary

This first plot I chose because I feel like it shows the distributions of emissions yearly contribution by each continent. The plot also shows how variable each of the continents are, for example, Asia holds the most number of people of all the continents and its emissions is also very diverse and variable, Asia of all the continents holds a diverse range countries, from contributing lowly to emissions to medium to contributing a lot, also noticeable is that Asia by itself, is normally distriuted. Other continents while also variable are not to that extent, Africa mostly contains continents on the lower end to medium, North America and Europe along with some Asia (most likely China) dominates the higher end with everybody else in the lower to upper middle.

This is a plot of three boxplots technically, comparing different features by Continents, the first shows how much of the worlds populations each continent has taken up, the second shows how the emissions per Continent and the final shows each continents per capita contributions to emission. The boxplot also shows how each continent varies in all three plots. The reason for this plot mostly is to add some context. Taking Australia and S.America as an example, South America shows a much higher yearly emissions than Australia, and while this might on the surface seem like all there is to it, adding in some context, Populations, we see that Australia shows a much higher per capita emissions than S.America, then looking at the populations by continent, we can see that S.America contains a lot more people than Australia and its emissions isnt bad at all at least compared to Australia.

The final plot shows the positive linear relationship between world population and yearly emissions. This makes sense since the more people there are, the more emissions likely would be generated. The reason for this plot is to visualize the three variables Continents, Yearly emissios and populations relative to each other. This plot shows a poitive strong correlation between populations and emissions yearly, it also shows the same movement for continents, so not only are the populations for each continent rising, the emissions for each continent is also rising. The continents are emitting more just as their populations are growing

Reflections

This has been an interesting dataset to work on, problems encountered are mostly related to wrangling the data and merging the individual datasets. The features were chosen intuitively, most worked well and revealed insightful information but some werent so fruitful.

There were a number of very interesting correlations from the start with the scatterplot matrix, although emissions yearly is highly correlated individually with both GDP and Populations, GDP and Populations arent necessarily strongly correlated. This makes sense since a rising population will or at least should contribute to rising emissions and also rising GDP implies a growing economy which also should contribute to rising emissions but a growing population wont necessarily by itself strongly drive the GDP of a country.

Another interesting pair of variables are the emissions per capita and Energy use. Energy use isnt necessarily highly correlated with emissions yearly but it is highly correlated with emissions per capita. This makes sense since both emissions per capita and Energy use are per capita, it is intuitive that the amount of energy used per person would be positively correlated with the amount of carbon emitted per person.

The correlation between Literacy rate and access to electricity is possibly due to the fact that individuals in more developed countries would have more access to electricity as well as education, I thought itd be interesting to add countrys literacy rate to this dataset so as to compare what correlation it has to emission, it made sense to compare this to emissions per capita since the literacy measures the rate for 15s & over for a countrys population. While this might seem counter intuitive at first, it actually makes sense since more developed countries would have a higher literacy rate and also a high rate of emission. The reason I say this seemed counter intuitive at fist is because I chose to add this feature hoping Id find a negative correlation implying that a higher literacy rate would mean a higher chance of awareness and education on global warming hence, lower emissions, while this is likely true, more awareness wouldnt necessarily translate to taking steps towards improving the situation. Besides, countries with low emissions arent necessarily doing so because of awareness or education, they usually are because theyre just not capable of burning that much carbon based fuel due to development. So it is possible for a higher literacy rate to mean lower emissions, it would however only mean lower emissions among countries with an already high emission and not compared to countries already with a low emission rate.

Jumping forward to the linear model built, since I chose two features of interest, I decided to build a different model for each, this was in part drived by finding different variables correlating with each of the features of interest. Russia was chosen as the test case because Russia is not in the dataset and I was able to find all the relevant data for Russia to test with. Both Correlation scores are looking pretty good, included in the mtable are coefficients and correlation scores for both. Both are over 0.9.

I definitely will keep working on this dataset as there are many more opportunities for finding interesting things from it, one thing Id like to look into in the future would be predicting what the global emissions would be like in the future and to look more into maybe comparing this dataset with a dataset if possible of natural disasters and to see if there might be a correlation between both.
